definition.value: A racemate composed of equimolar amounts of (R)- and (S)-nicotine.
Guanosine substituted with a methyl group at position N-1.
Inosine carrying a methyl substituent at position 1 on the hypoxanthine ring.
A guanosine where the hydrogens of the amine group at C-2 are substituted by methyl groups.
A quaternary ammonium ion that is the  conjugate acid of 4-(trimethylammonio)butanoate.
A hydroxy fatty acid anion that is the conjugate base of 2-hydroxyisobutyric acid, arising from deprotonation of the carboxy group; major species at pH 7.3.

A straight-chain 3-hydroxy monocarboxylic acid comprising a butyric acid core with a single hydroxy substituent in the 3- position; a ketone body whose levels are raised during ketosis, used as an energy source by the brain during fasting in humans. Also used to synthesise biodegradable plastics.

An N-glycosyl-1,3,5-triazine that is 4-amino-1,3,5-triazin-2(1H)-one substituted by a beta-D-ribofuranosyl residue via an N-glycosidic linkage. An antineoplastic agent, it is used in the treatment of myeloid leukaemia.
A group of heterocyclic compounds based on the 5-methyl-5,6,7,8-tetrahydropteroic acid skeleton conjugated with one or more L-glutamic acid or L-glutamate units.
6-Deoxoteasterone in which the hydroxy group at position 3 has been oxidised to the corresponding ketone.
A 3alpha-hydroxy steroid that is castasterone which is lacking the oxo substituent at position 6.
A 3beta-hydroxy steroid that is cathasterone which is lacking the oxo substituent at position 6.

Typhasterol in which the oxygen atom of the keto group has been substituted by two hydrogen atoms. A member of a biosynthetic pathway to castasterone, it has been isolated from the primary roots of maize.
An organic disulfide that is the L-cysteinyl derivative of glutathione.
An L-methionine derivative in which the sulfur has been oxidised to the corresponding sulfone.
An N-acyl-L-aspartic acid in which the acyl group is specified as acetyl.
An N-acyl-L-alpha-amino acid anion resulting from deprotonation of both carboxy groups and protonation of the amide nitrogen of N-acetyl-L-glutamic acid.
An L-methionine derivative that is L-methionine in which one of the amine hydrogens is substituted by an acetyl group.
An L-valine derivative in which one of the amino hydrogens of L-valine has been replaced by an acetyl group.
The N-acetyl derivative of phenylalanine.
An N-nitroguanidine compound having nitroso and methyl substituents at the N'-position
A member of the class of abscisic acids in which the double bond betweeen positions 2 and 3 has cis- (natural) geometry.
A tricarboxylic acid trianion that is the conjugate base of aconitic acid.
A tricarboxylic acid that is prop-1-ene substituted by carboxy groups at positions 1, 2 and 3.

Highly reactive chemical that introduces alkyl radicals into biologically active molecules and thereby prevents their proper functioning. It could be used as an antineoplastic agent, but it might be very toxic, with carcinogenic, mutagenic, teratogenic, and immunosuppressant actions. It could also be used as a component of poison gases.
A tocopherol that is chroman-6-ol substituted by methyl groups at positions 2, 5, 7 and 8 and a 4,8,12-trimethyltridecyl group at position 2.
A substance that opposes oxidation or inhibits reactions brought about by dioxygen or peroxides.
A substance that destroys or inhibits replication of viruses.
A pentitol that is the sugar alcohol produced by the reduction of arabinose or lyxose. It is found in serum or urine of human infected with Candida albicans.
An alpha-amino acid in which one of the hydrogens attached to the alpha-carbon of glycine is substituted by a 2-amino-2-oxoethyl group.
An alpha-amino acid that consists of succinic acid bearing a single alpha-amino substituent
Any of a group of compounds, both naturally occurring and synthetic, that induce cell elongation in plant stems (from Greek alphaupsilonxialphanuomega, "to grow").
A triol in which three hydroxy groups are substituted onto a benzene ring.
A group of heterocyclic compounds with a core structure containing a benzene ring fused to a diazepine ring.
A methylguanine that is guanine substituted by a methyl group at position 7. It is a metabolite obtained during the methylation of DNA.

A glycopeptide produced by the bacterium Streptomyces verticillus. The term, 'bleomycin' refers to a family of structurally related compounds. When used as an anti-cancer agent, the chemotherapeutical forms are primarily bleomycin A2 and B2.
An insecticide compound naturally occurring in plants.
